   <li class="comment byuser comment-author-mnwoods even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-59221">
       <div class="commentInfo">Posted by: mn_woods &#124; 12/18/10 &#124; 11:36 pm &#124; </div>
       <div id="comment-59221">
                      <div class="commentText"><p>I know some ISPs cap your max monthly data transfer, but the average user doesn&#8217;t come close to hitting that cap.  This is a stupid policy, but it only affects the small-ish percentage of people that download lots of data.<br />
.<br />
Now, if wireless carriers start this pay-per-click scheme, the average user base is much, much larger.  While grandma, mom, dad, and most non-techy people won&#8217;t hit that bandwidth cap imposed by their ISP, all of these demographics use smartphones to a certain extent (even grandma) and would be greatly affected by having to pay to access websites.<br />
.<br />
Also, LOL @ the suggestion that a mobile carrier could develop an offering that could undercut Netflix.  Maybe in price, but nothing else.  Who could or would want to devote the money and man hours to develop a strong recommendation system like Netflix has?  Or establish relationships with so many studios to provide the breadth of selection available from Netflix?  Case in point:  I work for a company that makes software that car dealerships use to profitably run their business.  Microsoft, which definitely has more R&amp;D and financial clout than my company does, has been trying to break into our industry for years; however, they have completely failed because they just cannot establish the right business contacts, sell to dealerships that already use my company&#8217;s and other companies&#8217; software, or chip away at enough market share.  It has been a lost cause for them.</p>
</div>
           <!--
           <div class="reply">
