   <li class="comment byuser comment-author-mekhongkurt odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-59225">
       <div class="commentInfo">Posted by: MekhongKurt &#124; 12/19/10 &#124; 5:22 am &#124; </div>
       <div id="comment-59225">
                      <div class="commentText"><p>On the face of it, this strikes me as a terrible way to go. However, one point I&#8217;ve not seen discussed &#8212; maybe I just don&#8217;t read websites that might have done so &#8212; is the economic angle from the carriers&#8217; perspective. That is, I wonder how much they spend versus what they take in? Is it reasonable return-on-investment, excessive, or in some cases maybe even too little (which I doubt)?</p>
<p>Let me interject I have no connection with any company involved in this push, and never have, so I&#8217;m not an apologist for greed when that&#8217;s a company&#8217;s only concern, i.e., driving profits ever up, both in real, inflation-adjusted terms AND as a percentage &#8212; only asking what the economic realities are, about which I know nearly nothing.</p>
<p>I will say that as a customer, I would MUCH prefer to pay a flat fee than any other model. I happen to be an American living abroad, and while the ISP&#8217;s here haven&#8217;t tried to go this direction, the cable TV service did so a number of years ago, offering various packages ranging from around $47 to about $83, with a very limited free option. And given the differences in the packages, to charge different prices &#8212; but flat ones &#8212; seems reasonable to me. Unless I&#8217;m missing something.</p>
<p>Anyway, I do know I don&#8217;t like the idea the companies want to see implemented.</p>
</div>
